{"cursor":"73244","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nThe 'MichelsonâMorley experiment' was performed in 1887 by Albert Michelson and\nEdward Morley at what is now Case Western Reserve University in Cleveland,\nOhio. It attempted to detect the relative motion of matter\nthrough the stationary luminiferous aether (\"aether wind\"). The negative results\nare generally considered to be the first strong evidence against the then\nprevalent aether theory, and initiated a line of research that eventually led to\nspecial relativity, in which the stationary aether concept has no role. The experiment has been referred to as \"the moving-off\npoint for the theoretical aspects of the Second Scientific Revolution\".\n\nMichelsonâMorley type experiments have been repeated many times with steadily\nincreasing sensitivity. These include experiments from 1902 to 1905, and a\nseries of experiments in the 1920s. In addition, recent resonator experiments\nhave confirmed the absence of any aether wind at the 10 â17 level. Together with the IvesâStilwell and\nKennedyâThorndike experiments, it forms one of the fundamental tests of special\nrelativity theory.\n","linknr":922,"url":"Michelson-Morley_experiment","recorded":1362484684,"links":70,"instances":["california","wave_propagation","physics","glass","programmer"],"pdf":["http://www.exphy.uni-duesseldorf.de/Publikationen/2009/Eisele%20et%20al%20Laboratory%20Test%20of%20the%20Isotropy%20of%20Light%20Propagation%20at%20the%2010-17%20Level%202009.pdf","http://www.exphy.uni-duesseldorf.de/Publikationen/2009/Eisele%20et%20al%20Laboratory%20Test%20of%20the%20Isotropy%20of%20Light%20Propagation%20at%20the%2010-17%20Level%202009.pdf","http://www.mpiwg-berlin.mpg.de/Preprints/P265.PDF","http://www.mpiwg-berlin.mpg.de/Preprints/P265.PDF","http://docuserv.ligo.caltech.edu/docs/public/P/P870007-00.pdf","http://docuserv.ligo.caltech.edu/docs/public/P/P870007-00.pdf","http://www.pro-physik.de/Phy/pdfs/ger_890_921.pdf","ht